context: In the <b8_0>vaulting events<b8_0/>, gymnasts sprint down a <a0_0>25 metres (82 ft)<a0_0/> runway, jump onto a spring filled board or perform a roundoff, or handspring entry onto a springboard (run/ take-off segment), land momentarily, inverted on the hands on the vaulting horse, or vaulting table (pre flight segment), then propel themselves forward or backward, off of this platform to <a1_0>a two footed landing<a1_0/> (post flight segment). Every gymnast starts at a different point on the vault runway depending on <a2_0><b5_0>their height and strength<b5_0/><a2_0/>. The post flight segment may include one or more <b6_0>multiple saltos or somersaults, and/or twisting movements<b6_0/>. A round-off entry vault, called <b7_0>a <a3_0><b9_0>Yurchenko<b9_0/><b7_0/><a3_0/>, is the most common vault in elite level gymnastics. When performing a <a4_0>yurchenko<a4_0/>, gymnasts "round-off" so hands are on the runway while the feet land on the springboard (beatboard). From the roundoff position the gymnast travels backwards and executes a backhandspring so that the hands land on the vaulting table. The gymnast then blocks off the vaulting platform into various twisting and/or somersaulting combinations. The post flight segment brings the gymnast to her feet.
